CALLBACK
1ï¸âƒ£ First: What does Synchronous mean? (Very basic)
ğŸ‘‰ Synchronous = step by step, wait for each line to finish
Example:
let a = 10;
let b = 20;
let c = a + b;
console.log(c);
Here:
Like 1 finishes â†’ go to line 2
Line 2 finishes â†’ go to line 3
Line 3 finishes â†’ go to line 4
JS waits for each line.

2ï¸âƒ£ What does Asynchronous mean? (Real-life analogy)
ğŸ‘‰ Asynchronous = donâ€™t wait, do it later
Example from real life:
You order food ğŸ”
Instead of standing at the counter, you sit down
When food is ready, they call you
That â€œcall you laterâ€ idea = asynchronous

3ï¸âƒ£ Now apply this to JavaScript
JavaScript itself is:
Synchronous + Single-threaded
BUTâ€¦
Some operations take time:
setTimeout
Fetching data from database
API calls

JS says:
â€œI wonâ€™t wait for these. Iâ€™ll continue running other code.â€
These are asynchronous operations.

4ï¸âƒ£ Your Code â€” What You EXPECTED
You wrote:
const student = getdata();
console.log(student);

You expected:
getdata() waits 2 seconds
Data comes back
student gets the value

ğŸ‘‰ This is synchronous thinking

5ï¸âƒ£ What ACTUALLY happened (VERY IMPORTANT)

Letâ€™s see your function:

function getdata() {
  setTimeout(() => {
    return { name: "bob", age: 12 };
  }, 2000);
}

Key truth:
âŒ setTimeout does NOT stop the function
JS does this instead:
Start timer (2 seconds)
Immediately exit getdata()
Return undefine
So:
const student = undefined;
Because:
ğŸ‘‰ The data is not ready yet
This is called:
âŒ Trying to use asynchronous data synchronously

6ï¸âƒ£ WHY return FAILED (This is the core confusion)

This line:
return { name: "bob", age: 12 };
ğŸš¨ It is inside the callback function, NOT inside getdata().

Think like this:

function getdata() {
  // starts timer
  // exits immediately
}
The return is like shouting an answer after the teacher already left the room.

So the value is:
Returned to nobody
Lost forever

==================================================================================================================
PROMISES

1ï¸âƒ£ Why Promises were invented (VERY IMPORTANT)
Problem with callbacks ğŸ˜µ
getData(function (data) {
  processData(data, function (processed) {
    saveData(processed, function () {
      console.log("Done");
    });
  });
});

âŒ Problems:
Code goes right â†’ right â†’ right
Hard to read
Hard to debug
Error handling is messy
This is called Callback Hell.

ğŸ“Œ Promises were created to FIX this

2ï¸âƒ£ What is a Promise? (Human language)
A Promise is an object that represents a value
that will be available in the future
Real-life analogy ğŸ’¡
ğŸ‘‰ You order food
ğŸ‘‰ You get a token
ğŸ‘‰ Token promises: â€œYou WILL get foodâ€
That token = Promise

3ï¸âƒ£ Promise has 3 states
State	Meaning
| State     | Meaning           |
| --------- | ----------------- |
| pending   | work not finished |
| fulfilled | work successful   |
| rejected  | work failed       |

4ï¸âƒ£ Creating a Promise (SLOW)
const promise = new Promise(function (resolve, reject) {
  // async work
});


resolve() â†’ success
reject() â†’ failure

5ï¸âƒ£ Real Example (Same as callback example)
âŒ Callback version (old)
function getData(callback) {
  setTimeout(() => {
    callback("Student Data");
  }, 2000);
}

âœ… Promise version (modern)
function getData() {
  return new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
    setTimeout(() => {
      resolve("Student Data");
    }, 2000);
  });
}


ğŸ“Œ Notice:
No callback argument
Promise returns a value later

6ï¸âƒ£ How to USE a Promise (.then())
getData().then((data) => {
  console.log(data);
});

ğŸ‘‰ .then() =
â€œWhen promise is successful, run thisâ€

7ï¸âƒ£ Internal flow (BEHIND THE SCENES)
getData().then(console.log);

Step-by-step:
getData() runs â†’ Promise created
setTimeout goes to Web API
Promise is pending
After 2s â†’ resolve() called
Promise becomes fulfilled
.then() callback goes to Microtask Queue
Event Loop pushes it to Call Stack
Code executes

ğŸ“Œ Microtask Queue has higher priority than callback queue.

8ï¸âƒ£ Handling errors (.catch())
getData()
  .then((data) => {
    console.log(data);
  })
  .catch((error) => {
    console.log(error);
  });
 
ğŸ‘‰ Cleaner than callbacks âœ”ï¸

9ï¸âƒ£ Reject example
function getData() {
  return new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
    let success = false;

    setTimeout(() => {
      if (success) {
        resolve("Data received");
      } else {
        reject("Error occurred");
      }
    }, 2000);
  });
}

ğŸ”Ÿ Promise chaining (IMPORTANT)
getData()
  .then((data) => {
    console.log(data);
    return "Processed Data";
  })
  .then((processed) => {
    console.log(processed);
  });
ğŸ‘‰ Each .then() gets previous result

1ï¸âƒ£1ï¸âƒ£ One-line interview definitio
A Promise is an object that represents the eventual completion or failure of an asynchronous operation.
